Evaluation and reasoning
- Why I reject Monsters of Rock Platinum Edition: on paper this release has many attractive surface features for me (crystal‑clear forward vocals, tight 3–4‑minute studio‑polished tracks, punchy arrangements, varied tempos, sing‑along anthems, and dynamics‑preserving remastering). However, it is explicitly a multi‑artist singles compilation. That format directly conflicts with my stated dislike of patched‑together anthologies that kill album flow and the value I place on cohesive sequencing and full‑disc listening. Even with good remastering, a singles compilation tends to prioritize immediate hits over sustained, cinematic arranging and consistent rhythm‑forward mastering across every track. The collectible, road‑trip/social listening orientation and 3–4‑minute singles focus also suggest a playback experience optimized for shuffled or casual listening rather than the carefully sequenced, detail‑revealing album experience I prize. In short: technically competent but structurally at odds with my preference for cohesive, sequenced discs that preserve groove and reveal arranging depth.
